	     <tr><td id="headerrow" colspan="2" class="mform" valign="top"><a id="sj" href="">RE: this is a tiny stick</a> <a id="fs8" href="#post"><img src="/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif" border="0" alt="Reply..." width="17" height="11" /></a>
	     <br clear="all" /><small>Posted @ Thu, Nov 21st 9:37 AM 2002</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform"><span id="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=108438"><span id="Sage">Aeldwan</span></a><br /><b><span id="Sage">Sage</span></b><br /><span id="notbold">63 posts<br /><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Good [3.66]</td><td valign=top class="mform" width="100%"><p>Actually what I think he is trying to say is this tiny little magical stick is a better weapon than what drops off of, for all intents and purposes, a god. The only reason is game play issues. I mean it WOULD be ludicrous in any fantasy setting for a stick, however magical, to do more damage than the sword (a weapon of specific destruction) of a god. But, since it's not affecting much, why NOT give those casters fantastic ratio weapons? Sometimes I really do think it's just to poke at the fighting types. <br/><br/>As an Enchanter I melee whenever I am color locking a target. Cheapest on mana, does about the same as our lousy DoT if not a touch more, (still us it and cripple on long fights with stunnable mobs) and I have to know if I am in range of my target when casting it. There are some pretty viscious proc weapons/spells we can use in this situation that can seriously up the damage too.<br/><br/>I sympathize with you though, my 47 warrior was out taunted and practically outdamaged by the Cleric yesterday in CoM. Those summoned hammers, and the Banish Undead procing toys from Hate/Fear are just ugly!<br/></p>&nbsp;<br /><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br /><a href=HTTP://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=397227 target=akztarg>Dutchess Buddercup Voxslayer</a><a href=HTTP://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=310389 target=akztarg>Master Aeldwan the Coercer</a> <br/>Primal Evolution, Morell-Thule<br/>"Doing the improbable daily to make the impossible seem easy"</td></tr>
